We reiterate our previous year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
(a) examine the noted vehicles in Annex B as to the ownership/or as trustee/donee to ascertain whether they are rightful to be charged under the Municipality, present documentation as warranted. Otherwise require the refund from the personnel concerned of the amounts corresponding to the value of gasoline issued for use of non-government vehicles;
henceforth, stop providing gasoline/fuel to privately-owned vehicles against Municipal funds pursuant to Section 340(e) Volume I of GAAM;
require the concerned drivers to prepare the trip ticket judiciously prior to trips leading to the completion of data needed in the trip tickets; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the information provided in the trip tickets prior to allowing payment thereof.

We reiterated and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Officer thru the Local Development Council (i) continuously refer to the JMC for appropriate guidance in crafting the Annual Investment Program and inclusion of PPAs on the 20% DF that will aim to fully attain the desired socio-economic development targets of the Municipality, with emphasis on the recent issuance on the utilization of the fund and inclusion of budget intended for the implementation of CBMS to aid in planning PPAs in the Municipality; (ii) present in detail the PPAs charged against the 20% DF in the Annual Investment Program (AIP) to dispense the need to secure such SB approval for the timely implementation of the development projects, otherwise, seek approval from the SB of projects charged to the appropriation described in generic terms;
direct the Municipal Budget Officer to take note of improper charges noted in item 7.20 of this report to warrant the strict utilization of the 20% Development Fund to only eligible expenditures and, ultimately, maximize the Fund’s intended purpose. Refrain from charging these items or provide allotment, appropriately under the 20% Development Fund;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) submit the aforecited deficient documents identified in Item 7.23.4 for further evaluation of the Audit Team; (ii) check the noted deficiencies in item 7.23.5 above, in conformance with the processes and documentary requirements stated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 to avert the recurrence thereof on future similar undertakings; and (ii) ensure the completeness of the documents submitted prior to payment.

We reiterated and supplement our previous year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
require the BAC, BAC Secretariat, and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of RA 9184, its IRR and relevant rules and regulations in the Municipality’s procurement process by:
paying attention to the procurement lapses noted above to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements;
enforcing the required payment of bidding documents before the deadline for the submission of bids;
furnishing COA with copies of all purchase orders/contracts and all papers relative thereto within five days after the perfection of the contract and sending of notification of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries to the Office of the Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001 and 95-006;
ensure direct payment of claims to suppliers is utilized as a means of payment of obligation instead of reimbursement;
observe the threshold set by the IRR on the use of alternative modes of procurement;
submit the noted deficient documents of the projects as appearing in Annex C.1 and C.2, for further evaluation as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action; preparation of an explanation/justification on other deficiencies noted also mentioned in Annex D; and look into the noted deviations on the procurement of goods and infrastructure projects, to avert the recurrence thereof on future similar undertakings; and
henceforth, on similar undertakings on infrastructure projects, a) conduct complete detailed engineering prior to the preparation of bid documents to assure the viability of infrastructure projects; and b) conduct materials and items of work testing by the Municipal Engineer or the Project Engineer.
instruct the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made; and (ii) facilitate the deduction of retention money that will serve as warranty from defects of procured infrastructure projects.
consider creating a separate office for the BAC Secretariat or hiring additional personnel assigned to assist in the review of bid documents to minimize errors and improve compliance with RA 9184.

We reiterated our previous year’s and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive (LCE), in coordination with the MENRO agreed to:
align targeted plans and programs in reference to the plan strategies defined in the 10-year SWM Plan, towards attainment of envisioned goals and objectives;
continue to intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay, following the strategies identified under the approved 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the Municipality;
comply with the minimum requirements for segregation, storage of solid waste pending collection and volume reduction specifically on the provision of separate properly marked containers for each type of waste and initiate ordinances and regulations mandating residential units and all commercial, institutional and industrial establishments within the Municipality in reference to Section 2 of the Act;
in coordination with the Sangguniang Bayan fast track the amendment of the existing “No littering” ordinance ascribed under Municipal Ordinance No. 012 series of 2018, to account for the issuance of citation tickets and imposition of community service as a penalty;
exercise the strong political will to implement the applicable ordinances pertaining to Solid Waste Management, particularly on the aforementioned “No littering” ordinance.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation and made supplemental recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
in coordination with the Municipal Treasure continue with the efforts made on withholding and remittances of taxes in accordance with the aforequoted regulations;
exert effort to identify or obtain information on the source of the uncorrected discrepancy amounting to ₱13,849.62 observed in last year’s report;
look into the cause of the variances between the withheld amounts and remittances made on all funds and make the adjustments/amendments to BIR returns, if necessary and allowable, on noted discrepancies in prior years and CY 2023;
exercise prudence on the use of appropriate tax rate in the computation of withholding taxes, especially for suppliers, to avert the recurrence of the mismatch on the recorded and actual remittance of taxes withheld as cited in item 1.12 of this Memorandum; and
henceforth, ascertain that taxes all withheld are remitted intact to the BIR.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:

require the refund from the personnel concerned of the amounts corresponding to the value of gasoline issued for use of non-government vehicles;

henceforth, stop the practice of providing gasoline/fuel to privately-owned vehicles against Municipal funds pursuant to Section 340(e) Volume I of GAAM;

require the concerned drivers to prepare the trip ticket judiciously prior to trips leading to the completion of data needed in the trip tickets; and

Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the information provided in the trip ticket prior to allowing payment thereof.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
consider the disposal of the vehicles that were identified as beyond economic repair and use the proceeds from the disposal thru supplemental budget as additional funds for the purchase of new vehicles;
direct the Municipal Accountant to keep a maintenance/repair record of each equipment/vehicle owned and operated by the LGU to aid in the monitoring if vehicles meet the conditions of “beyond economic repair” for appropriate disposition;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer (GSO) to review the deficiencies noted for future compliance prior to payment of expenditures.

We restated and the Management agreed on our prior year’s audit recommendations and made additions thereto that the Local Chief Executive:
reduce the amount spent to serving meals and snacks during ordinary staff meetings or conferences in order to prevent the incurrence of unnecessary expenditures;
pay all claims directly to the supplier and avert adopting reimbursement as a mode for payment of expenses in consonance with Section 93 of PD 1445;
consolidate all future purchases (planned events) for the year and employ competitive bidding for meals and snacks served during ordinary staff meetings or monthly conferences and for the entertainment of guests and visitors to be assured that advantageous price for the LGU was obtained; and
for procurement through shopping/small value procurement, instruct the members of the BAC to provide for a wide dissemination of the Municipality’s procurement activities in order to obtain/attract more suppliers.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendations and made additional recommendations that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
instruct the LDRRMO to (i) prepare annual LDRRMFIP and incorporate it with the Municipality’s AIP; and (ii) include the unexpended balance of the fund in the LDRRMFIP which should also be included in the AIP for proper planning and utilization of the Fund;
require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit a Report on the Sources and Utilization of the Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund (DRRMF), through the LDRRMC to the COA Auditor on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;
strictly adhere to the issued guidelines of fund transfers specially on the compliance with reporting requirements and utilization thereof; and
see to it that PPAs charged against fund transfers are incorporated in the LDRRMP and are integrated in the Medium-term and Annual Investment Program as called for by the above-quoted regulation.

We restated our previous recommendation and made supplemental recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require the GAD Focal Point Person (GFPP) to:
amend the GPB to match the pre-prepared GPB with the approved appropriation in the annual budget for the budget year, subject to the review and approval of the DILG;
closely monitor the implementation of the programs and projects embodied in the GPB and intervene immediately if delays in the implementation are observed and amend the GPB, if warranted;
conduct gender analysis using the HGDG tool in the attribution of the GPB; and
in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO), to work on the establishment of a GAD database and the maintenance thereof for a more gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation specifically on attending the required technical orientation on the usage of the CBMS.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
trace the unremitted balances starting from the current and recent periods to bring about the proper remittance thereof;
make sure that the same amount withheld is remitted the following month;
maintain a complete Index of Payments for proper monitoring of claims and for prompt and accurate recording and remittances to GSIS, PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG; and
assign/appoint a personnel who will act as a checker, to monitor the withheld amounts on payrolls vis-a-vis the remitted amounts, prior to settlement of mandatory contributions to concerned government agencies.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendations and made supplemental recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require the:

end-users or implementing units in the next budgeting period to prepare Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) as basis of the budget for the ensuing year; 

Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat to 

(i) consolidate submitted PPMPs to be used as basis in the preparation of Annual Procurement Plan (APP); 

(ii) enforce the required payment of bidding documents before the deadline of submission of bids; 

(iii) secure a copy of Certification from the Insurance Commission of the surety bonds posted by the suppliers/contractors by sending confirmation letters to the issuing insurance company which they will forward to the Insurance Commission;  

(iv) comply with the requirements in preparing the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) specifically defined under DPWH Department Order No. 197, series 2016; and 

(v) observe the threshold set by the IRR on the alternative modes of procurement and other deficiencies noted under item f.3 of this memorandum;

BAC, Accounting and other officers concerned to submit the required documents discussed above in accordance with RA 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 for further evaluation as basis for Audit Team’s subsequent audit actions; and

Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive and the Local Development Council 

(a) continue to include projects that have long-term development impact to the Municipality and its constituents; 

(b) reduce/limit the amounts earmarked for expenditures that do not partake the nature of capital investments such as labor payroll for solid waste management as such can be charged to the General Fund proper; 

(c) avail of relevant data/statistics and stakeholders’ analysis in proposing projects/programs under the 20% DF guidelines so that the same can bring high-impact and responsive long-term benefits to a wider base of beneficiaries; 

(d) refer to the utilization of the 20% Development Fund under DILG, DBM Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2017-1 in developing the Municipality’s Annual Investment Plan and PPAs for the 20% DF to improve and attain the desired socio-economic development of the Municipality and achieve improved quality of life to the marginalized sector.

